	<div class="blogbody">
	
	<a name="001161"></a>
	<h3 class="title">Review form</h3>
	
	<h3>What to look for in the paper</h3>
<ul>
<li> <b>well-structured</b>: Is the paper clearly organized? Does it have an initial overview, a final summary, and is its structure logical?
<li> <b>well-written</b>: Does the paper use good prose, reasonable sentence length, correct grammar usage?
<li> <b>well-motivated</b>: Does the paper identify important issues(s) to address? Has the paper considered alternative view points?
<li> <b>focused</b>: Does the paper have a clear central narrative (not too many digressions)?
<li> <b>situated</b>: Does the paper show an awareness of relevant papers?
<li> <b>exemplified</b>: Are analogies are intuitive and  clearly explained? 
<li> <b>accessible</b>: Are technical terminologies explained on their first use? Is the paper reasonably self-contained?
</ul>

<h3>Format of your review</h3>

<ul>
<li> What do you think is the thesis of this paper? Briefly, outline the author's argument for the thesis of the paper.
<li> What are the paper's major strengths and weaknesses?
<li> Discuss the originality of the ideas presented in the paper.  
<li> Provide feedback to the author on ways to improve the paper with respect to the criteria above.  For example:
<ul>
<li> Is the paper easy to follow? Would you recommend a different way to organize the paper?
<li> Point out glaring grammar errors and typos.
<li> Are there aspects of the argument that you would like to see the author pursue further?
<li> Are there more suitable analogies that the author could have used?
</ul>
<li> Provide any other comments you may have about this paper.
</ul>

	
	
	
	<div class="posted">Posted by hwa at <a href="https://www.cs.pitt.edu/~hwa/cs1590/archives/001161.html">12:13 PM</a>
