		<h2 class="date">
	September 09, 2008
	</h2>
	

	<div class="blogbody">
	
	<a name="001142"></a>
	<h3 class="title">Writing Assignment #1</h3>
	
	<p>In his article, <i>Reason, Relativity and Responsibility in Computer Ethics,</i> Moor (1998) argued that computing technologies sometimes bring out situations for which there are policy vacuums.  Johnson (1997), too, conceded that "the issues have a new twist that make them unusual, even though the core issue is not."  Choose an <b>old</b> technology or innovation (e.g., telephone, railroads, electricity), and discuss what issues arose about them.  Analyze the issues in terms of one of the ethical frameworks discussed in Chapter One of CyberEthics (the small text book).  Compare the issues to current concerns about computing technologies.  What solutions have been developed?  To what extent can they help to address the new concerns about computing technologies?

<p>**This topic is based on one of the suggested term paper topics in A Gift of Fire (Baase, 2003).

<h3>Due Dates</h3>
<ul>
<li> <b>By noon 9/18</b> you should turn in (via email to the TA) one paragraph on your topic plus a list of <i>at least</i> five references about your chosen technology.
<li> <b>By noon 9/25</b> you should turn in (via email to the TA) a first draft of your full paper. You should also bring two hard copies of your first draft to class.
<li> You will receive two papers written by your classmates. You will have to review them.  A review form will be provided.  <b>By noon 9/30</b> you should send your reviews to the authors of the papers (you should also return to them the edited hard copies).
<li> <b>The full writing assignment is due by noon 10/7</b>  You should turn in all of the following in hard copies in class: the final version of your paper, the two reviews from your reviewers (and the earlier drafts that the reviewers edited).
</ul>

<h3>Guideline</h3>
<ol>
<li> Your paper should be between 3 - 5 pages (about 1000 words).  The paper should express your views.  You should support your position with sound reasoning and evidences.  You are encouraged to use well-reasoned analogies in your arguments (e.g., Moor used money, war, privacy and copyright as examples of informational enrichment), but avoid having just anecdotal evidences as your support.
<li> Use 12-point Times New Roman, with 1.5 line spacing.  The margins should be: 1" for top and bottom, and 1.25" for the sides.
<li> Your paper should be written carefully, using good English style, with proper grammar, punctuation, and spelling.
<li> Divide your paper appropriately into relevant sections, with their own headings of your choosing
<li> Your paper must contain properly formatted citations to the literature, and include a properly formatted bibliography, if appropriate.
</ol>
<h3>References</h3>
<ul>
<li> Baase, S. (2003) <i>A Gift of Fire: Social, Legal, and Ethical Issues for Computers and the Internet</i>, 2nd. edition. Prentice Hall.
<li> Johnson, D. (1997) " Ethics On-Line," in <i>Readings in Cyberethics</i>, (eds.) Spinello and Tavani. pp. 30-39.
<li> Moor, J. (1998) "Reason, Relativity, and Responsibility in Computer Ethics," in <i>Readings in Cyberethics</i>, (eds.) Spinello and Tavani. pp. 40-54.
<li> Spinello, R. CyberEthics: Morality and Law in Cyberspace, 2nd edition. Jones and Bartlett Publishers, 2003.
</ul>
	
	
	
